  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concern—it's a real, lived experience that affects people like me, who've seen firsthand how it can undermine confidence and performance. Growing up in a family where both parents had advanced degrees, I was encouraged to pursue education, but I've also witnessed how the pressure to conform to stereotypes about who belongs in science and technology can leave even bright students feeling like they don't belong. For instance, when I was in high school, I remember a math teacher saying, 'You're not cut out for this,' after I asked a question that was slightly more advanced than what was expected. That moment, though small, planted a seed of doubt that lingered long after. Now, as a delivery driver in Los Angeles, I see how stereotype threat plays out in everyday interactions—like when people assume someone who doesn't have a college degree can't understand complex technology. It's not just about the stereotypes themselves; it's about how they affect mental health, especially for those already struggling with depression. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it needs systemic change. Schools should create inclusive environments where students feel safe to ask questions without fear of judgment. Mentors and educators must actively challenge stereotypes by highlighting diverse role models in STEM fields. And for me, as someone who's been through it, I believe in the power of community. Volunteering with local STEM outreach programs has taught me that when we lift each other up, we can break down barriers. But it's not just about programs—it's about changing the culture in schools, workplaces, and even our own conversations. If we want to see more people from all backgrounds thrive in STEM, we need to address the root causes of stereotype threat head-on, not just treat the symptoms.",
